messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
12.	Panzer Gang (Andrew, 3-15)
It really breaks my heart to see my dear old friend Andy go down to the worn out place again. He knows the sound of the door closing on his season, and he’s heard that sound before. He wonders if Taylor and Evans know him anymore; they’ve wrapped themselves into my team like a chain, and now I’m never afraid my championship hopes will die. You can dance in a stormy season, but only if your standings are in last place.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Belichick Yo Self (Jack, 6-12)
Jack might stink at fantasy, but we learned last night that he’s pretty good at DMing. Maybe stick to that!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 6-12)
Matt’s really bad at fantasy, and really bad at tanking. Who would’ve thought that he would still have a 0.33 win percentage when he basically threw in the towel in week 2? I mean, I’m not criticizing you sir. I’m sorry. I just meant… maybe you’re doing this wrong? No no, I’m wrong. You’re right. Please don’t hurt me Matt.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 7-11)
Zach’s been bullish on his chances, but the reality is he hasn’t broken 80 points in three weeks. Before you feel too sympathetic about his 0.5 point loss this weekend, two weeks ago he still earned a H2H win – a narrow 0.66 point victory over Matt. Sounds balanced to me. Just how like we can all dunk on Zach now, but he can access and hold us hostage over our internet history any day he pleases. Perfectly balanced!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Questionably Mediocre (Izzy, 8-10)
There’s some movement at the bottom of these thanks to some H2H matchups. Izzy has now risen to 8th, which is probably as high as I can justifiably rank him despite how much I like him as a person. Where does our universal fondness for Aaron come from? Probably his perfectly manicured facial hair. It’d be a shame if he was ever persuaded to shave it… perhaps live on a poker night…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 9-9)
Hunter’s team is as much as an enigma as Codsworth von Discovercards’ business dealings. Conner and Swift have quietly become elite RBs, and a Hill/Godwin receiver corps looks about as good as any contenders’. But Mahomes’ slump and trouble finding flex production has him facing Black Friday: keep fighting for a playoff spot but risk missing it, or sell to rebuild the Discovercard fortune but lose ambition points?

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 8-10)
Because of the small resolution of Sleeper profile pictures, it took me a long time to figure out what Dan’s was. At first I thought it was a picture of someone doing a line of coke. A few weeks later, I realized what I thought was a table was actually a person’s face and the two fellows were kissing. A month later, as I was writing this ranking, I realized that person is Tom Brady and the person kissing him is presumably his son. Finally, Dan’s profile picture and name makes sense! Took me long enough. About as long as it’s taken Dan to determine if he’s really a playoff team. Hurry up and decide, because it seems like I need to trade for your fucking kicker.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Je Ne Saquon (Shawn, 10-8)
My unbridled hatred for Florida men blinded me to the potential of Shawn’s team. But since he told me he’ll be moving back to Maryland eventually, he has salvaged my evaluation of his character and his position in these rankings. He still has some question marks – will Saquon return soon, who can he reliably flex, did he vote for Ron DeSantis – but Shawn’s still squarely in the playoff picture.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 11-7)
Patrick’s rising up these rankings faster than Justin Jefferson can careen down the field to throw a block. Think losing two of the most valuable players in fantasy – Murray and Henry – would slow him down? The bold move to snag Elliot said otherwise, and he enjoys above-average options across all his starters and bench. Don’t forget that Henry could still return in time for championship weekend, just like how Patrick could return to poker any week and win $30.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 13-5)
Welcome to Ben’s pity party! Our cause for celebration: despite leading the league in points for, Ben’s only 6-3 in H2H matchups. He’s third in the league in points against (which is even more impressive because he doesn’t play himself and can factor out his own points for). Best of all, his kicker put up a big fat 0 this week, while Mark’s scored 9.9 – a difference greater than the margin of victory. The man who advocated for no kickers get it handed to him. He has been vindicated! Woohoo!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 13-5)
I’ll usually give the tiebreaker to whomever just won the H2H, and Mark picked up a big one against Ben this week. In a terrible game for the Rams offense, Cooper Kupp still posted 15 points, a floor that should terrify the rest of the league. Of the remaining contenders, Mark’s depth is clearly the worst, especially outside of WR. He’ll need his players to dodge major back injuries better than he could.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 14-4)
For the first time this season, Rick’s reached the pinnacle – the top of these rankings. Now that you’ve done it, can you quit trying so hard? Rick has earned 10 wins in a row, has sure-fire elite starters at each position, and excellent bench options to absorb any bad injuries. But Rick tends to enjoy arbitrary honors like power rankings, groupme likes, and NACURH awards more than substantive prizes like fantasy championships, so maybe if we all give him lots of internet points he’ll put in less effort and give us a chance.

messages.text: So I'm not running a power ranking myself, BUT it's hard to look at these playoff projections and say that they're dramatically wrong. Maybe the seeding moves around, maybe Hunter swaps out with Dan. But despite all the craziness in the middle of the pack this year, does this really seem so unbelievable? We have 5 weeks left in the season, so things can certainly change. But will they?

messages.text:

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
7) Verma Efficiency Index, distance 42
For not the last time, I'll remark that 42 ties the score of the best ranking Power Ranking of Week 1. So you tell me - are GroupMe likes actually decently indicative of fantasy performance, or were the early power rankings just full of shit? How can anyone really say that their early power rankings were any good?

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
6) Andy Awards, distance 22
Let me reiterate real quick, my Ⓜ️ethodology is pretty clear - look at league rankings at the end of the week and compare to power rankings. Andy does not try to predict league rankings. Andy only predicts a given week's scores (minus kickers, which can mean a lot if you ask Ben this week). The fact that he put up only 22 distance points this week is incredible. Maybe our teams are just stretching apart that far, or maybe Andy's algorithm is better than it looks

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
5) Dan's Power Pyramid, distance 19
Very weird thing here - this is the first odd number distance score we've yet had. I legitimately didn't believe it was possible, but I checked and double checked and the number is correct. Thanks to the methodology that Dan uses, he's actually an odd number of overall places away from the correct picks. Basically any shakeup at the top of the pile wrecks his chances of being the best rankings for the week, and that's what happened. Also the 3rd and 4th tiers remain a mystery and will continue to plague these rankings.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
4) Ben's Power Rankings, distance 12
4th place might seem disappointing for what is arguably the canonical power rankings of the league. But his distance score is still only 12 and his mistakes are small (undervaluing Patrick, overvaluing Zach). It hurts to see him in the middle of the pack here but it's hard to say that he's truly off the mark.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
3) James Madison, distance 10
Ties the previous record, so congrats to our fourth president. He made an effort to correctly predict the teams in the middle of our league and did a good job, but he did especially well at the top as he was the only one to correctly predict Rick being #1. Yay Madison! He's now in my top 5 favorite presidents.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T1) Fowler Power Hour, distance 8
A new record! Just not as cool. Maybe I should go back to bribing this guy, maybe if I had then he would've placed me #1 and had a distance score of 6. Instead he went ahead and had an absurdly accurate ranking on his own. Coward.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T1) Schlaich Superiority Score, distance 8
A new record! And he gets the credit because he ranked me better last week than Mark did since they both ranked me the same this week! Zach's data-driven approach remains effective. He's been upset about his VEI score, but not to worry because I've liked literally every single one of his messages in this chat the past week. I'm on team Zach all the way, let's go Zags!

messages.name: Dan Laffin
messages.text:
The SNF/MNF Median Report:

All but certain to beat the median:
Mark (At 77, Projected 136)
Rick (At 97, Projected 128)
Ben (Final 111)
Shawn (At 97, Projected 111)

All but certain to miss the median:
Andrew (At 45, Projected 76)
Zach (Final 77)
Matt (Final 79)

In the running for the final TWO spots:
Patrick (Final 102)
Hunter (At 70, Projected 92) (Claypool + Boswell)
Dan (At 72, Projected 91) (Tannehill)
Aaron (At 67, Projected 87) (J. Jones + Rams)
John (At 68, Projected 83) (D. Johnson)

It seems likely that Patrick will hold on to a median win despite four teams with players left still in the running. For Patrick to miss the median it would require two of the four teams to exceed their projections by 10 or more. What seems to be the likeliest scenario is that after SNF, Patrick will sit in fifth for highest current score with either me or Aaron in sixth. It will then come down to Hunter and maybe John to see if their MNF players can step up for that last median spot.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
Now that we've reached the midpoint of the season, I wanted to remind everyone about playoffs/seeding/etc:
-Top 6 teams after week 14 make the playoffs. Record tiebreaker is total PF
-Playoffs will run weeks 15-17
-Top 2 teams get a bye in week 15
-Playoff matchups are head to head only, no vs. median
-Bottom 6 teams make the Toilet Bowl bracket, but for the purposes of the league punishment/draft order, final standings after week 14 will be used
-Draft order will be determined just like the NFL -- reverse standings order for first 6 picks, 7-8 will be the playoff losers from week 15 (final standings will be the tiebreaker), 9-10 will be the playoff losers from week 16, 11 will be runner-up and 12 will be league champion, with snaking still in effect
-This means we have 6 more weeks of the regular season and 3 for playoffs -- @Andrew Tran  might want to start looking at plane tickets to Denver before flights fill up

messages.text:
12.	Panzer Gang (Andrew, 3-13)
Andrew’s two wins this week must have Matt shaking in his (hiking) boots!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: 11.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 5-11)

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Belichick Yo Self (Jack, 6-10)
Congrats Jack, you unlocked one of my elusive Achievements! This one: have your QB score under 12 fantasy points in a week their team puts up 44 real points. Wait, another Achievement too! Roster three Bengals. No way… an unprecedented third Achievement… Draft a WFT player in the second round and still have him as a critical starter by week 8! You’re somehow better at getting these Achievements than beating Andrew. Oops, one more Achievement: Lose H2H to Andrew’s wildly uncompetitive team! Keep it up Jack!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	Questionably Mediocre (Izzy, 7-9)
Absolutely in love with the called shot Izzy made for Randall Cobb: he picked him up as soon as Davante Adams was ruled out, and watched Cobb make 3 catches for 15 yards… and 2 TDs. The rest of this team looks Izzy took a few more shots before the draft, though.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 8-8)
Hunter’s barrage of trade block messages felt like a classic coaching move: he’s just signaling to his team that no one’s job is safe. Hunter’s a disciplinarian, like a Joe Judge, Brian Flores, or Mike Zimmer. I expect Hunter to have similar success as those coaches this year !

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 7-9)
Zach’s stinginess in trade talks might need to abate if he wants to become a true seller. His overperforming RBs regressed hard this week, while his bench of Prescott, Hunt, and Adams looked like a graveyard worthy of Rick’s above cabinet space in Commons. The panic button on Stefon Diggs had to get smashed weeks ago too. We’ll see what the “head of the company” has to say about this team next week if he makes a few trades.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 9-7)
Having the most valuable player in fantasy just means you have that much more injury risk. And when your bench as thin as a mint, it means you tumble down the power rankings. Patrick has a few options to replace Henry but none of them provide league-winning upside. If he wants to climb back up, he could earn a lot of respect from me by rolling out the Aaron Jones/AJ Dillon Green Bay backfield like a total chad.6.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 9-7)
Having the most valuable player in fantasy just means you have that much more injury risk. And when your bench as thin as a mint, it means you tumble down the power rankings. Patrick has a few options to replace Henry but none of them provide league-winning upside. If he wants to climb back up, he could earn a lot of respect from me by rolling out the Aaron Jones/AJ Dillon Green Bay backfield like a total chad.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Je Ne Saquon (Shawn, 8-8)
Sigh… Fine, fine fine. Shawn you can be ranked in the top 5. Only as a treat. I still don’t trust Mixon or Barkley as far as I can throw them, McLaurin and Shultz are TD dependent, and Herbert’s come crashing back to earth. But you changed your schedule to go see Dune with me and I must show respect for that.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 8-8)
Dan’s proud announcement that he will not be joining the ranks of the tankers not only restored my faith in this league, but also makes total sense. Anything can happen in playoffs and Dan is still in fine shape to make them. We can all support Ridley’s leave of absence, but from a fantasy perspective, he was already wildly underperforming his draft position anyway. Dan knows a thing or two about positions. He’ll be in a bargaining one as he shops for a replacement.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 11-5)
Mark falls not one, but two spots this week; hard to rank him above Rick when he just lost the H2H. It’s also hard to be as high on this team when Dalvin Cook put up only 7.8 points in a plus matchup. That coveted first-round RB is only RB27 this year, btw. First round picks do not guarantee performance folks. Except for mine next year. Guaranteed RB1 or WR1. Lots of trade value to be had…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 12-4)
Rick quietly hasn’t lost a H2H or vs. median game since week 4. The emergence of Darrell Henderson, AJB and Ja’Marr Chase has covered up some major draft and free agent missteps (re: $101 free agent Younghoe Koo is currently K19) but the return of CMC will only raise this team’s sky-high ceiling.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 12-4)
Mark’s stay at the top of the rankings was short-lived. With Derrick Henry going down, Ben now has a great shot at having both RB1 and RB2 on the season. His shrewd move to pick up former Redskins Hall of Fame running back Adrian Peterson could pay big dividends later in the season, too. (He played for the Redskins and will go in the Hall of Fame. This is not a spin.)

I'd be interested to see a MATT-style analysis in the off-season to see what would've happened if everyone kept their drafted team and never traded - I have to imagine that the MATT would've been fairly accurate. messages.text:
5) Andy Awards, distance 22
Even though my methodology for the Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️ doesn't help the Awards, Andy still put in an excellent showing this week. With a few more tweaks to his algorithm, Andy could end up with an elite power ranking.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
4) Dan's Power Pyramid, distance 20
Dan's tier structure actually makes a lot of sense for this league, and by keeping Mark, Ben, and me in the top two tiers and Andy/Matt off the pyramid, he's put up a lot of points. But he moved me off this week and that cost him, though putting Patrick closer to the top was an inspired move.

Ben's rankings are solid as always and even currently put Patrick at 4th, but again who can tell what will happen in that crazy middle, especially now with Derrick Henry out.

In sole possession of first place is Zach, who called the top 3 and bottom 2 in order and got close on the rest. Those other 7 players remain incredibly difficult to place; as soon as one looks like they deserve to be in 4th like Dan was last week (the SSS put him in 4th), they drop back down.

messages.name: Dan Laffin
messages.text: Of these six, four will get median wins. There are a ton of potential finishes in regards to the exact order of the six. Really exciting! I am the only one with a completed score and currently three of the teams are already ahead of me. Which means the only way for me to hold on to a median win would be a complete meltdown of the Chiefs offense that prevents Patrick AND Hunter from passing me. Assuming that does not happen, it becomes a five-team footrace to secure four median wins. This very well could come down to the last drive and even potentially the last play. Huge game.

messages.name: Dan Laffin
messages.text:
Going into MNF, there are seven(!) teams that still have players yet to play. That makes the median race quite exciting.

All but certain to beat the median are:
Rick (Projected/Final at 128)
Ben (At 90, Projected at 125)

All but certain to miss the median are:
Matt (Projected/Final at 63)
Zach (at 61, Projected at 70)

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 5-9)
There’s not much left to say about these last two teams that hasn’t already been said, so I’ll just use this space to tell Matt that he’s a bad spades player. Matt, you’re a bad spades player! Please don’t team with me next time so I can be with the guy just before you…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Questionably Mediocre (Izzy, 5-9)
There’s not much left to say about these last three teams that hasn’t already been said, so I’ll just use this space to tell Izzy that he’s a great spades player. Izzy, you’re a great spades player! Please team with me next time instead of this next guy…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	Belichick Yo Self (Jack, 6-8)
Jack was due some regression in my rankings and it finally caught him. Gibson’s been hampered by injury, Lockett hasn’t scored more than 8.2 points since week 2, and Keenan Allen’s been supplanted as WR1 in LA to Mike Williams. His mid-season slouch has been the opposite of what happened to Shawn. He does get style points for being the first manager in league history to flex a TE, though. Cool flex, is ok.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 7-7)
Hunter built a team around teams, but with the Mahomes/Hill and Tucker/Ravens DST stacks flailing he’s been left to rely on James Conner TDs. Which, for some reason, has been a somewhat viable strategy for the past several weeks. Edmonds has been vultured more than these swine carcasses I’ve been leaving across the wild west in my Red Dead Redemption II playthrough, or as I prefer to call it, Hunting Simulator 1895.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	Je Ne Saquon (Shawn, 7-7)
I think I have some bet about eating my rankings if Shawn makes the playoffs, and I’m getting hungry. He has enjoyed a roster-wide mid-season bounce-back that has really turned his season around, and he hasn’t given up future draft capital to do it. Shawn is nothing if not a man without principles so there’s nothing he can’t do if he doesn’t apply him self in the other way.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 7-7)
Achievement unlocked: win a H2H matchup with an empty starting slot! Another achievement unlocked: whine about Mark’s low PF but win a H2H matchup while scoring under 80 points! Zach’s decision was certainly informed by his pairing against Matt, and I’m not even sure how he fit 8 players on his bench. He certainly gets style points.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 8-6)
Another team that other rankings may be a little low on, there aren’t any holes on Dan’s roster… except the empty bench spot he kept over the weekend. Classic Dan move. Apparently it gives him some sort of edge in the waivers, but that matters less since we use FAAB, but nothing matters if he’s still able to snag Gainwell for only $20. I’ve kind of confused myself. Maybe that’s been Dan’s play all along, you devious bastard.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 7-7)
I think the rest of the league is a little low on Patrick. He proved he could do what no Egyptian has done and exploited the Israeli tank to get Jones. Henry/Jones is an elite RB corps that could easily push him to a championship run, and he has QB1 candidate Murray to boot. WR, flex, and special teams leave something to be desired, but this is absolutely a team that could slay the championship dragon that’s guarding Fiona.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 10-4)
Like Mark, Rick’s ripped off 4 consecutive wins over the past two weeks, posting over 140 points each time. Unlike Mark, this has less to do with shrewd management (Hubbard and Kmet were merely replacement level) and more about the emergence of Ja’Marr Chase, a potentially league-winning draft move Rick made in the 6th round. I’ll openly admit I was on the Penei Sewell train, but to the credit of Cincinnati (and the chagrin of you Ravens fans), Chase has been nothing but bank.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 10-4)
Ben slides a little by losing both of his previous H2Hs and barely sneaking out with vs. median wins (he had the 6th highest score both weeks). On the other hand, he’s cleared his byemageddon hurdle and maintains a relatively healthy roster with high upside. He has to be hoping the Chiefs and Travis Kells figure things out soon, though. (Apparently, that spelling of Kelce is closer to how it’s supposed to be pronounced, so we’re gonna make it a thing.)

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 11-3)
Credit where it’s due – Mark has won big on his way to the league’s best record, and he’s done it through shrewd management. Cordarrelle Patterson, Khalil Herbert, and Seal-Jones have all come to play while some of Mark’s big names have sat out. He’s also gambled with rookie receivers Smith and Waddle without getting burnt. Conventional wisdom would suggest the Stafford/Kupp stack is due for regression soon, especially in the TD department, but the rest of this team is more than capable of picking up the slack.

7) Verma Efficiency Index, 46
A bit of a black mark here for just straight up disincluding Izzy, as the VEI's distance score would've dropped to 38 if he had put Izzy in, even at 12th. The VEI remains the greatest thing about this group and I'll fight to the death to defend it, even though it's a terrible measure of fantasy manager skill.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
6) Andy Awards, distance 32
To be fair to Andy, my methodology hurts him. His Awards predict the upcoming week's PF, rather than the overall standings and team strength. That said, he had me and Shawn at 7 and 8 and we blew through those expectations. Maybe I'll start comparing the Awards to that week's scores in the future to see how they do.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T4) Ben's Power Rankings, distance 14
Not too long ago, 14 would be a stellar distance score but now it's barely enough for the top 5. Ben's nameless power rankings are still very strong but he's still having trouble placing John/Jack.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T4) Schlaich Superiority Score, distance 14
As is tradition, tiebreaker goes to whomever ranked me higher. Zach's algorithm is getting better with age, much like a fine wine or Zach's mom. Excited to see where these rankings go, and even more excited to see the beautiful charts continue.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
3) Hunter's Scallop Carpaccio, distance 12
A change in the methodology this week has significantly helped Hunter. I'm including his scallop rankings rather than his penis lengths because right now I am hungry and not horny. It works out for him because he's already jumped up to the top 3. I think it's impossible to have an odd number distance score, so really he's only down by 1 from the top two ranking systems.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T1) Fowler Power Hour, distance 10
A new record! But he gets listed below Dan because he's the only one in the whole league that didn't put me in the top 3. Mark remains a great fantasy manager, power ranking writer, friend, and scholar, but just a terrible terrible person.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
T1) Dan's Power Pyramid, distance 10
A new record! Dan's pyramid continues to be a strong tracker of actual rankings and lines up well with projected playoff berths. Expect him to continue doing well, but again, he has a built in floor because of the way the tiers work. We'll see how he does in Week 8 after I take sole possession of 1st place

messages.text:
The projections going into SNF and MNF put the six winners as:
Rick, Hunter, Patrick, Mark, Zach, Aaron - with John and Ben just outside.

Those who have no* chance to beat the median this week include myself, Shawn, Andrew, and Matt.

Here are the eight to watch:
Rick: Currently at 90, projected at 139
Hunter: Currently at 131, projected at 131
Patrick: Currently at 111, projected at 130
Mark: Currently at 88, projected at 126
Zach: Currently at 107, projected at 124
Aaron: Currently at 101, projected at 123
John: Currently at 94, projected at 121
Ben: Currently at 116, projected at 116

Hunter and Ben are all done for the week and currently sit in the top six. But as Hunter can most likely sit back and enjoy the win, Ben will hold his breath as his total is chased down by the six other contenders.

We'll see what it looks like at the end of the game tonight. But there's suddenly a serious chance this comes down to the wire tomorrow night.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
12.	Panzer Gang (Andrew, 1-7)
Andy graciously relieved Ben of the title for the league’s lowest score, failing to even break 50 points this week. My understanding when he made the trade with me was that he still intended to put up enough wins to avoid Waffle House, but with Matt accidentally getting to .500, it’s hard to see how Andrew will make that happen… Unless Sleeper’s owned by Daddy Gates… in which case we might experience unusual interference in our league very soon.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 5-5)
Somehow, Matt simultaneously sucks at fantasy football and tanking in fantasy football. He (accidentally?) picked up two wins this week starting Josh Jacobs, Chuba Hubbard, Rondale Moore, and Zach Schlaich at Flex. Just kidding, Zach’s not as fast as Henry Ruggs. Or even Ben, as the SC Diner race proved. But would Matt beat them both in a race? He would certainly win in the Amazing Race, given his previous world-traveling experience.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
GOAT: Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
He holds the record for the league’s highest score, so he’s technically the greatest manager of all time for this league. I thought it only appropriate to put this section before the real-life GOAT:

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 4-6)
It’s unclear if Hunter put Mahomes on the trade block as a joke (as he told me) or for serious strategic reasons (as he probably should). The Mahomes-Hill stack could be a deadly asset, but they aren’t performing to their potential, and it’s a luxury Hunter probably can’t afford with serious questions at RB2, WR2, Flex, and bench. Another luxury Hunter can’t afford? These complimentary cashews he puts out for house guests. I mean, I love cashews as much as anyone, but do you really have to offer the most expensive nut? Neighbors are stopping by just to grab handfuls and we’re getting fleeced. Gotta think peanuts or almonds have to be in 9 Dorset Court’s future.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	Je Ne Saquon (Shawn, 5-5)
I’ve teased Shawn about Saquon’s availability, but I never root for injuries, and Barkley’s ankle sprain will seriously impact this team’s comeback bid this season. You gotta wonder if Barkley will even get a second contract in New York. Despite being one of the most objectively talented and physically gifted players to ever enter the league, his limited availability and lack of production might catch up to him in free agency. He’s like a modern-day Trent Richardson. But enough about Saquon, let’s talk about Shawn… well, he’s just a modern-day court jester. A CLOEN! Now tank and trade me players for my super team, coward.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐: Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
Did I mention Ben is unreasonably handsome?

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Questionably Mediocre (Izzy, 4-6)
Izzy finally made a team name, and it perfectly encapsulates where he’d land in the team name power rankings. And in these actual team rankings. And in the league player favortism rankings… just kiddin’. You’d still win that one, Izzy. And I’ll keep hammering this point until someone proves me wrong. In the meantime, Izzy better hammer the table for more Aaron Jones receiving TDs, because that might be the only way he turns this season around.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 4-6)
Despite his 4-6 record, Zach has the league’s second-highest points for, perhaps a negative indictment of the vs. median league setting. And despite the frequent ridicule of his WR-heavy draft strategy, Zach quietly has 4 (!) top-21 RBs. Even if they’re due for some negative TD regression, Zach might be due for some positive W/L progression. OK Zach, now that I’ve been nice to you in this passage, will you finally become a good faith trade negotiator?

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 5-5)
Patrick unlocked an achievement: have Derrick Henry post 130 yards and 3 TDs and still fail to pick up a H2H or median win. Much like the Titans themselves, Patrick is highly star-player dependent: Henry, JJefferson and Baby Yodray could easily combine for 90 points, but when they struggle like this week, the rest of this roster can’t pick up the slack. Similar to how Patrick’s law school team partners are inevitably going to shit the bed on his group project, forcing the law boi to skip another 6 weeks of poker. Don’t worry Welling, our difference in poker +/- isn’t growing in your absence…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Belichick Yo Self (Jack, 6-4)
Jack’s narrowly won a H2H matchup while under the median two weeks in a row, suggesting his record is somewhat inflated relative to overall team ability. But like the Chief’s Inflated Officer – the best team name I’ve ever encountered, thanks Rick – Jack’s ready to put CEH on IR. He’ll have to roll with… Antonio Gibson??? Who was somehow on his bench in favor of a Steelers WR? This WFT slander must stop.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5. Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
This word doc really doesn’t like all these doubled numbers, but we’re making it work for the sake of the poll. Who would we be if we were not beholden to our righteous Groupme polling overlords?

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 6-4)
Dan’s always preferred fat and long over narrow, and this weekend’s narrow H2H loss to Matt has gotta make him sore. Metcalf, Kamara, and Andrews are finally coming alive, but injuries have made RB2 and WR2 less clear than a Tinder pick up line. How exactly am I supposed to respond to claim about relative shaftments?

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
A respectable fourth place: Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
The only respectable thing about Ben is his humility making these rankings.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 6-4)
Make no mistake, Rick’s team is 1337, but his top two receivers (AJB and Thielen) are second fiddle on their own teams and his presumed backups (Hollywood and Chase BANK) are unproven and due for negative TD regression. But Rick’s cleverly nicknamed every player, so it’s all cool. Who else is cool? That old man by the sea, the most necessary reference that Rick shit the bed on…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3. Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
Ben also gets to be ranked 3rd thanks to a solid trade with Panzer Gang before this weekend, and thanks to Rick’s poll!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2 (actually).	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 7-3)
Mark did well to take care of business against the Panzer Gang, but he’ll miss the vs. median win during an otherwise bye week. Other misses: Kittle, recently put on IR; and Dalvin Cook, the first-rounder he traded up for that hasn’t been nearly as available or productive as a first-rounder needs to be. Mark’s still in good shape for a postseason push, but this team isn’t going to make the baby without a little more magic.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2. Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
Ben’s so good he’s also ranked second. Plus he has the best record in the league, enviable depth, and 80 points more in the PF category to the next closest player.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
A week after his starters combined for 1 passing and 1 rushing touchdown for the lowest score in league history, Ben’s starters combined for 4 passing, 3 rushing, and 8 receiving touchdowns en route to the league’s first 200+ score.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
0.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 7-3)
The boy is back in town, at the only number above (or would it be below?) 1.

Shawns Power Rankings Rankings based on how much joy they give

5) Verma Efficiency Index, distance 46
Our newest entrant (and ftr I'm using last week's data here) is not even designed as a fantasy power ranking, but it goes into the list anyway. Shawn brings us one step closer to every person having a ranking so I can finally include the Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️Ⓜ️ into itself and the snake can eat its own tail. These rankings were basically wrong this week btw.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
4) Schlaich Superiority Score, distance 34
This ranking is a perfect encapsulation of Zach as a fantasy manager. Generally smart picks, a solid lineup, but just way too high on his own team. Might explain why he was lowest on the Verma Efficiency Index this particular week.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
3) Ben's Power Rankings, distance 30
Always an enjoyable set of rankings, and Week 4's was universally beloved as one of the best. Ben seems to unreasonably hate Shawn though, which probably has more to do with the fact that Shawn never cleaned the panini maker.

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
2) Fowler Power Hour, distance 28
Fortunately Mark noticed, completely unprompted, that my top two overall draft picks got injured in the first quarter. Unfortunately, that did not justify the high position he put me in. He was higher on Patrick than most rankings though, which represents excellent prescience

messages.name: Rick Mikulis
messages.text:
1) Dan's Power Pyramid, distance 27
Somehow rigid, unchanging colorful shapes were more accurate than anything else this week. It's worth noting though that if Dan had just listed everyone as tied for 1st, that would only be 9 distance points more. Personally, I love this method because it's just about the only thing I'm a top in

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
12.	Certified Lamar Boy (Andrew, 1-7)
Andrew! Congrats! Welcome to the winner’s circle!!! Thank goodness we were one of a hundred leagues that instituted a vs. median win so you could taste the sweet flavor of victory this weekend. Did you know that when your RB scores a TD you get a Sleeper notification? Did I know I would get a text notification from you when you’re ready to tank? Yeah, I had a feeling…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 3-5)
If Matt’s really trying to tank, I’d ask him to justify spending $69 FAAB on Chuba Hubbard… sheeeesh. I’d also ask him how he can sleep at night knowing the only reason he was remotely competitive this weekend was his Bills D/ST putting up 24 points. Finally, I’d ask Matt if he’d fly with me to Pamplona to run with the bulls, which remains a bucket list item for me and something that I feel confident he’d agree to.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Team TheVermanator (Shawn, 4-4)
What’s that? Barkley’s actually a top-10 RB so far this season? OK fine, but Mixon’s week to week with an injury, so I still have an excuse to rank Shawn as a bottom 3 team. It doesn’t hurt that McLaurin, Schultz, Boyd, and dare I say Woods had some of the best performances they will this season to elevate Shawn to the league’s top score. It does hurt to think that Shawn invited DeeDee as his +1 to a wedding instead of the homeboy he lived with for 3 years…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 2-6)
Week 4 is officially late enough to evaluate draft results realistically. And for Zach, that’s a bad thing. Adams and Diggs haven’t come close to pulling their weight as first and second round picks – part of the danger of picking from a volatile WR position over RB early in the draft... It’s also late enough in the season to know that you need Ws instead of just potential at this point, and at 2-6, Zach’s looking like an enemy of the state instead of a playoff team.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 4-4)
Testament to this league’s balance that a 4-4 team lands at 8th in these rankings. I will say it every week apparently, but Hunter goes as Mahomes and Hill go, and when Hill goes 11/186/3 Hunter will pick up at least one win. We don’t need to mention that his other 5 skill position starters combined for less than 33 points. Kinda like we don’t need to mention how easily Ben can hear Hunter’s gnarly sickness shits from his bed. That’s a detail no one deserves to know, or experience…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 5-3)
Is anyone really surprised that Derrick Henry is RB1 after 4 weeks? It makes Patrick’s swap from 2nd overall to 4th overall look that much more shrewd. If Patrick keeps making shrewd moves like that throughout his legal career, you’d be well advised to lock him in as your attorney for a friends and family price now... Goodness knows some of you animals are going to need legal help sooner rather than later.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Team izzyfoshizzy8 (Izzy, 4-4)
We should all be happy since Izzy went 2-0 this weekend and Izzy is clearly this league’s most favored member. If we were all to preference rank people in this group, I’m confident Izzy would be the winner by far. This seems like a totally non-toxic, positive social experiment we should try out... Also non-toxic: Darnell Mooney’s 125 yards in Justin Field’s second start and AJ Dillon’s 15 carries.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 5-3)
Dan’s stomach might’ve been doing backflips during Sunday Night Football, but he should be pretty settled by the results his Fantasy team put up this weekend. Former Terp DJ Moore has asserted himself as a top-10 receiver through 4 weeks, while kicker Tyler Bass has become a near-lock for 10+ points a week. Dan will need more production from his QB and RBs to stay feisty, though… kinda like he’ll need more product to review for 6/12/18/24 confirmation.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Belichick Yo Self (Jack, 5-3)
Jack really thread the needle here to snag the H2H win but miss the vs. median win, a window of about 6 points. He took some gambles during the draft, but Hurts and Zeke Elliot have actually panned out as a top-5 options at their position through 4 weeks, which has bailed out an otherwise mediocre team and bench. The real question is if Jack is a top-option at Assistant Capital Director for the Department of Transportation... Apparently, Rick and the rest of the Massachusetts government would disagree.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 4-4)
Just like Ben, Rick laid a log in his pants this week and picked up two losses. Injuries are mounting but there’s no doubt Rick would prefer to be well over .500 after all the assets he gave up building this roster. He’ll need players to recover rapidly to remain a championship contender. Since this is Rick’s first fantasy football rodeo, I’ll let him know: when you’re dealing with injuries, you can’t afford to roster two QBs, D/STs, or most of all Kickers… What’s that? Rick’s been playing fantasy for nearly 10 years? And he’s still making dumbass moves like this?? Man Rick is dumb. SO fucking void of intelligence. Really stupid, stupid, stupid.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 5-3)
If your players are gonna shit the bed, they might as well all do it all in one week... Ben’s 5 skill players not named Ekeler logged 141 yards and 0 TDs total en route to the lowest score in league history. But with bench players Edmonds, Singletary, Carter, and Anderson all getting plenty of involvement on their offenses, plenty of optimism remains for this egocentric league manager.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 6-2)
A third person has been crowned #1! Mark joins Ben and… what the hell… Andrew???... as the only people to hold this slot, and for good reason. Picking up at least 1 win when Cook and Kupp have down days is huge, and it gave him the best record in the league. Mark should be pretty pleased with his depth as well, but it’s easy to wonder how much better this team could have been with Adam Thielen as an extra contributor.

messages.text:
7.	Team izzyfoshizzy8 (Izzy, 2-4)
Izzy’s team has been really head-scratching through three weeks. Here has been his scoring ranks so far: 10th, 3rd, 12th. It’s been feast or famine, and this week was decidedly hungry. Looking at his starters, it’s hard to discern why or how he should address this. Maybe it’s just variance. Or maybe, just like the rest of us, he’s just a big “fan” of oscillating !

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 2-4)
Who would’ve thought that Zach’s putrid running backs would carry him to the league’s third highest score? And who would’ve thought that Zach would take the H2H L anyway? His nail-biter against Mark was a fun distraction during poker night, but not picking up two wins when his RBs actually show up might cost Zach later if he makes a habit of it.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 5-1)
Mark earns bonus points for straight-up good management: picking up Peyton Barber last minute proved to be a winning move (and Barber’s play is a jab in the heart to this WFT fan, since they released him at final roster cutdowns). The rest of this roster looks feisty, and if Mark can keep picking up wins while Cook is out, he’ll be well on track for a playoff push.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 4-2)
Difficult week for Rick. Glass half full: two of his starters went down early in their first quarter and he still snuck away with 1 win this weekend. Glass half empty: CMC, AJ Brown, and Darrell Henderson are all now week-to-week injury wise, and Conner, OBJ, and Hollywood Brown have all become week-to-week performance-wise. Rick might struggle with consistency for the next few matches and Mark’s breathing down his next. It’s nerve-wracking enough to make you piss your pants.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 5-1)
Only 2 of Ben’s 9 starters reached their projected scores and he still put up over 100 points and a H2H win. Swapping the week’s WR1 Mike Williams for Mattison literally 30 seconds before kickoff actually cost him a vs. median win too, but as long as Dalvin Cook misses time Ben will run 4 deep at RB and WR with high end starters at QB and TE.

12.	Team TheVermanator (Shawn, 0-4)
Shawn is refusing to tank and has rejected each of my outrageously unfair trade offers. But when you’ve benched your round 1 RB after week 2, you should know you’re in dire straits. Cmon Shawn, I just want Younghoe Koo. A 2024 14th is a steal for you..

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 3-1)
Matt might have the worst 3-1 roster in America right now. After selling the barn for 2022 picks, his lineup is ghastly. He apparently has no desire to compete this year and has already admitted to me that our matchup this week is a “wash,” which means he’ll probably beat me in a demonstration of poetic justice. Incredibly, he still doesn’t have the worst team in the league.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Certified Lamar Boy (Andrew, 0-4)
Our favored first-year player has got off to a rough start, but it’s not for lack of effort; he’s making solid lineup choices and came close to a vs. median win this week. It just seems that he got a couple of players that might turn out have been overvalued in the draft (Robinson, Taylor, Harris) because their offenses haven’t turned out. At least Andrew’s graphs are turning out excellently, especially the ones with fancy ~labels~

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 2-2)
Hunter should revel in the Ravens’ big Sunday night win, but he better hope Baltimore didn’t expose a strategy to beat KC. Their bracket coverages sold out to stop Tyreek Hill from beating them deep, which resulted in a bad fantasy day for Hunter’s WR1 and a modest score for his second-round QB. It’s like a smoker with wild temperature swings: as that QB/WR stack goes, so will Hunter.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 3-1)
Patrick might have the most top-heavy team in the league: Murray, Henry, and Jefferson might all be top-5 at their position, but he probably doesn’t have another player in their position’s top 25. Cashing in with double Ws on weeks like this where Murray and Henry have monster games will be critical for Patrick to keep up, otherwise he’ll fall behind more than he is on his law school reading. Close GroupMe and get back to it slacker!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 1-3)
Zach’s Cooper-Dak stack attack held him back; even though the quarterback rarely took a sack, the other Cowboy hack caught fewer passes than a fullback. Zach might have something with Dallas’ second halfback, especially if Kellen Moore goes into his backpack to unfurl a throwback rushing attack. Zach’s hoping for a different runback this week as he seeks payback against the league member with the whack back.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 1-3)
Dan leapfrogs Zach here not because of a better week, but from better roster management – after a couple aggressive trades, Dan’s starters look real nice (as long as the Seahawks look real nice). With decent depth, Dan’s in a good position to sit tight and focus on piling up wins like a stack of waffles.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Team izzyfoshizzy8 (Izzy, 2-2)
Big rankings correction for Izzy this week after several of week 1’s concerns were addressed. The news of Aaron Rodgers’ demise was greatly exaggerated; Green Bay looked great in a big bounce back for their offense (even if Rodgers looks absolutely devasted after every bad play - for real, watch him closely next game). Julio’s first 100-yard game with Tennessee is also as promising as Izzy is as a partner is spades. Must be nice to get paired with him and not some cloen.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Belichick Yo Self (John, 2-2)
John was a notable beneficiary of the vs. median matchup, as he put up the fourth-highest points but lost his H2H. Say what you want about Northeastern graduates, but at least they’re compassionate fellows, as John humbly aided Patrick with his TE problem via a trade that doesn’t seem to improve his own team at all. Rick’s also told me all about the times John helped him change his pants after pissing himself in the office. What an upstanding guy!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 3-1)
The Stafford-Kupp stack could be a serious problem for the other players in the league. But then again, so is body odor, and that hasn’t stopped any of you pigs yet. Mark’s bench looks a little stinky too after week 2, but it’s nothing he can’t Waddle away from.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 3-1)
The most aggressive player so far in the trade market, Rick’s already leveraged a significant portion of his 2022 draft but has acquired a top-notch roster with considerable depth. There’s a ton of season left, but even after week 2 it’s interesting to think if the H2H loss to Ben in week 1 will be a factor in playoff seeding.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 4-0)
After gingerly putting himself at 1st in these last week, Ben immediately justified himself by putting up the highest score and becoming the last undefeated team. How a league half-full of Ravens fans let Lamar Jackson fall to the last pick of the fifth round is still a mystery, but the advantage he and Kelce provide at their positions can help make up when a player like Sanders gets stuck in the dunes.

12.	Team TheVermanator (Shawn, 0-2)
Well, at least I nailed this in the first rankings. Saquon is clearly not himself and he might burn those who drafted him in the first round for the second year in a row. Mixon looked great, and Damien Harris put up solid yardage, but those players aren’t going to combine for 58 touches very many more times this year. The rest of the team is bleh, the bench is bleh, and Shawn is bleh. Ship it in and tank already. Now trade me McLaurin.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick, 1-1)
I have much respect for Patrick on the felt but almost none on the virtual gridiron. Ok, that’s definitely an overreaction after week 1… or is it? Henry and the Titans might be in trouble, CEH might struggle behind that rebuilt offensive line, Pittsburgh is still spreading the ball around enough to make all 3 of their starting receivers just attractive enough to start in fantasy even though they will regularly disappoint, Jarwin might be TE2 to Schultz (Patrick has a TE problem LOL), and Jeudy is going to miss some serious time. Combine that with the ghastliest bench I’ve seen in any league this year and I see why so many youths today have so little respect for the law and its Boys.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Team izzyfoshizzy8 (Izzy, 0-2)
If alarm bells are going off for Dan and Andrew’s teams, Izzy already needs to smash the panic button. No roster has more questions after week 1 than this. What the hell happened with Green Bay’s offense, and how long will it hold back Rodgers and Aaron Jones? Ditto for Mike Davis in Atlanta and Julio Jones in Tennessee. How did Mike Gesicki finish with 0 catches? Izzy stays in the 10th ranking here because Hopkins and Samuel got off to very strong starts, Latavius Murray could be a massive pickup, and the stars on this team still provide a ceiling higher than a few clowns got in the forest in my backyard. But week 2 will need to give some answers.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	Certified Lamar Boy (Andrew, 0-2)
I still believe in our first-year fantasy player, but it is clear after week 1 that previous evaluations might have been generous. Najee Harris got off to a pretty rough start to justify being an RB2, while Mike Evans and JuJu were far from their team’s first passing option in week 1. Zach Moss and Rhamondre Stevenson, viewed by us and pundits alike as great values in the draft, cratered expectations with a healthy scratch and 2 touches and a fumble respectively. Like Dan, Andrew has pieces to compete, but he’ll need to do some work to remain competitive. C’mon man, I got a 10:1 bet on you winning this thing.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan, 0-2)
Dan saw he was first in my rankings last week, hit that Bugs Bunny “No,” and put up the second-fewest points. There are some serious alarm bells going off for Tannehill and Ridley’s offenses, while Ronald Jones was the worst player started in the league with -0.6 points. For each bench player that exceeded expectations (Hines, Beasley) another one greatly disappointed (Michel, Sutton). The star power is still here for this team to make a deep postseason run, but Dan got off to the worst start possible.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	The Zany Zebras (Zach, 1-1)
Zach’s team is tough to evaluate after week 1. The Prescott/Cooper stack looked great, at least with a favorable game script, and it’s hard to believe Diggs and Adams can do much worse than they did this week. On the other hand, James Robinson had about as good of a matchup as he will this season and only had 6.9 points (nice) while Kareem Hunt was bailed out by a TD and 2pt conversion. Melvin Gordon might be a backup option, but he got 70% of his week 1 points on a fluke long touchdown run and Zach’s already put him on the trading block. If Zach can figure out RB, look out, but it will be a tough problem to address with basically 2 starting spots up for grabs.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Mahomes’ Modern Life (Hunter, 2-0)
A 2-0 team that just put up the most points coming in 6th? The roster don’t lie. I’m sure the Mahomes/Hill stack will bail Hunter out several more times this season, but he’s facing a massive problem: Mostert is out for the season and Hunter has absolutely no startable replacement lined up. There’s reason to be concerned about Claypool and Ravens D after week 1, as well. Hunter’s moving up these rankings, but with reservations – we’ll see how that impacts my shaftments.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	Rebuilding year (Matt, 2-0)
Matt’s putting players on the trade block like he’s ready to tank but you wouldn’t guess that looking at week 1 scores. His starting lineup was rock-solid despite down days from Golladay and Andrews, while Agholor, Gronk, and famous Jameis inspired some confidence in this roster’s depth. Maybe Matt will just view them as more ammunition for next year’s draft, especially since he needs an extra 3rd for a certain Michael Thomas…

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	Belichick Yo Self (John, 1-1)
John benefited the most from week 1 reevaluations. Jalen Hurts looked great, and if that wasn’t a fluke against a bad Falcons D, this roster looks a lot better. Ty’Son Williams, Jamaal Williams, and Corey Davis had great weekends on his bench, which makes Aiyuk’s disappearance a little more palatable. If Pitts can make a turnaround like Hurts, this team could have a ceiling as tall as the John Hancock Tower.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	The Trolly Problems (Mark, 2-0)
To prevent myself from falling precipitously down Mark’s own rankings, I don’t think I can rank him any lower than 3rd, but he deserves this slot anyway. The Stafford/Kupp stack had a very promising start to the season, and Mark might not even miss trading away Adam Thielen with Higgins, Brown and Waddle waiting in the wings. There’s still some uncertainty with those players, and several players already look like obvious drop candidates, but no trolly should have a problem with Mark after week 1.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	10,000 Rats (Rick, 1-1)
Ok, now do away with that power-rankings-are-standings impression again, because I’m ranking a 1-1 team in second. Rick did put up the third highest points this week, and that was despite Josh Allen having a bad game and an “input error” with OBJ at flex. With McCaffrey not skipping a beat and several bench players exceeding usage expectations, Rick still has plenty to be optimistic about despite the H2H loss. Another roster that looks quite solid all around.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben, 2-0)
A few of you are under the mistaken impression that these power rankings are merely a reflection of team records. Any list of that sort would be absurdly useless, especially after just one week, and if you’re interested in the standings you can conveniently find that on the Sleeper app under “League.” I will, however, leverage that impression to justify putting Ben at the top of this week’s rankings – something I don’t do lightly or often (just ask others who have seen my rankings before). Jackson had by all accounts a bad night and still put up 18 points, a strong showing of his floor, while Ceedee Lamb ate 15 targets and Kelce justified his first-round status. Questions persist about Ben’s WR2, but Mike Williams might have a big year in store, while Singletary might have a closer hold on RB1 in Buffalo than previously thought. After one week, this is still the most confidence-inducing roster top to bottom.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
12.	Team TheVermanator (Shawn)
I might’ve given Izzy crap for drafting Carlson and Murray, but at least they’re on a roster – Shawn you’re a Patriots fan, right? You know they cut Cam Newton, right? You know you drafted not one but two of the riskiest high-end RBs, right? You know your only RB backups are both in crowded committees, right? You know starting Hooper at TE is possibly worse than Jarwin, right? You know you should probably roster a defense, right? Right? RIGHT??? Shawn, you’re last in the preseason power rankings – and you’d be last in the team name power rankings too, buddy.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
11.	Lamar’s Modern Life (Hunter)
Hey there roomie 😊 I know you’re probably disappointed to be this low, but I also know you’re big on personal responsibility. So I think you’d actually be happy to hear that actions have consequences and well, you’ll have to live with the implications of going Hill-Mahomes in the first two rounds and overdrafting Ravens special teamers. It just means you have like, 1 or 2 other good players on a team of 15. So, you should really be happy, because this is justice – and Batman loves justice!

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
10.	Rebuilding year (Matt)
At least Matt is being upfront with his name. Maybe he though we were a non-PPR league since he targeted RBs that don’t catch passes and WRs that are more apt for bomb touchdowns than reliable volume. I would almost forgive the egregious Michael Thomas pick too if this wasn’t otherwise the worst bench in the league: two QBs, a backup TE, a Texans RB, a Patriots WR, and a rookie WR on a crowded offense. If you’re reading this and so shocked you’re about to swap apps to go check, nope, I’m being dead serious. Thank you Matt for helping me learn spades, but please let anyone, literally anyone, help you with this bench.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
9.	The Zany Zebras (Zach)
Zach scooped both Davante Adams and Stefon Diggs, which means he has as good of chances at having the season’s WR1 and WR2 as anyone ever has. It also means that he has to start Kareem Hunt and James Robinson at RB, which is grosser than Zach thinks beer tastes. A couple questionable bench decisions also bog down what could otherwise be a serviceable roster. Everything might be salvaged by his value pick of TE Logan Thomas, who somehow survived late despite the absurd deny-Welling-all-TEs-run.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
8.	Belichick Yo Self (John)
Kind of like most people from New England, John’s team is highly average. He has great starters at RB and WR but might face a big drop off at Flex/backups. He also took massive leaps of faith by drafting Jalen Hurts and Kyle Pitts as starters, moves that are more likely to tumble him down the standings than lead him to the championship. Nonetheless, it can’t be too bad because he got to homer pick his defense. Can’t imagine what that’s like.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
7.	Thattle Dewdonkey (Patrick)
LOL, this dumbass gets to start Blake Jarwin. Peasant. He also gets to start Henry, CEH, J Jefferson, and Kyler Murray, which would be pretty great if he didn’t have a bum TE, LOL. The rest of the starters have some serious question marks, especially at TE, LOL. Pretty cool bench too BUT STILL NO TE LMFAOOO

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
6.	Team izzyfoshizzy8 (Izzy)
Like Izzy himself, this team is easy to love. Big names abound on a team that balances floor (Aaron Rodgers, DeAndre Hopkins) with upside risk (Gus Bus, Julio Jones and Mike Davis). He also built a great bench that could produce several starters. The only problem is that Izzy somehow decided to draft not one, but possibly the two of worst players currently rostered in the league, Daniel Carlson and Latavius Murray. You might want to take a mulligan on those (and on your Bengals/Cowboys stack in the other league you drafted while inebriated – but hey, much respect).

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
5.	10,000 Rats (Rick)
With Josh Allen, McCaffrey, OBJ, AJB, and Waller, Rick’s team features as much ceiling as anyone in the league. Indeed, among starting rosters, Rick’s got as much firepower as anyone – like he’s someone who picked the rats and eagles. Rick’s problem is that he picked the water buffalo and wolves for his bench. It’s a disaster, and the Conner/Tonyan trade won’t change much. Low-ceiling QB, players who have repeatedly demonstrated unreliability, and rookie WRs on medium- to bad-offenses doesn’t suggest that he’d last long against even the hunter and the crocs.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
4.	The Trolly Problems (Mark)
Mark took a unique approach to the draft and team building, but it looks to have paid off in paper. He sought volume and stacks: Stafford/Kupp in LA and Cook/Thielen in Minnesota have high floors while offering point explosions on good days. Mark was also able get volume monsters Montgomery and Kittle at value. Overall, it doesn’t look like Mark gave up much among his starters to get the elite RB he really wanted – except it looks like the trolly fatally rode over his RB depth. He’s only rostering 3 RBs, so he’s a bad tackle to Cook away from starting Tevin Coleman or someone off the wire.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
3.	Hit Quads like Saquon (Ben)
Perhaps the most solid roster top to bottom, Ben’s team lacks the ceiling found in Dan or Andrew’s, but boasts great starters at all skill positions and has the deepest bench in the league. The room full of Ravens fans passed him Lamar Jackson for great value, who will combine with TE Kelce to drive major positional advantages. This is a team that is built for the whole season – hopefully it lasts longer than Ben did in the games of Vietnam and Afghanistan in the basement.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
2.	Certified Lamar Boy (Andrew)
Andy looks poised to continue the age-honored tradition of exceeding all expectations in the first year of playing fantasy football. Or, maybe he’s not burnt out like the rest of us old farts and actually did some research or something. Whatever Andrew did, he also successfully built a high-floor juggernaut that should compete every week. There is some volatility at RB given uncertainty surrounding Harris and Taylor, but they are also in situations that easily post monster numbers. He even got value with a homer pick, the WFT Defen… oh wait, you denied that to your good buddy Ben. Hope you feel good about that. (You honestly should.)

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text:
1.	Tom Brady’s Son (Dan)
First lesson of law school: draft your fantasy team during class. Maybe he was just trying to be respectful to the others in that classroom he was sitting in for some reason on a Sunday afternoon, but Dan quietly killed this draft. Elite RB1 and WR1, check. Huge volume RB2 and WR2, check. High floor QB and TE, check. Flex might take a few weeks to sort out but he has several enticing silver bullets on his bench, including Courtland Sutton who could be a league-winner if he returns to pre-injury form. This is a textbook balanced, disciplined team, and it wouldn’t surprise me if Dan beats league median every week.

Other possibilities:
- I've also seen settings where only late picks in the draft are eligible to be keepers. So for example starting at round 8 (and ending at round 16) is the range where you can keep players the following year.
- Some leagues have a cap on how many years you can keep a player (I've seen anywhere from 1-4 years).

messages.name: Patrick Welling
messages.text:
Hey guys I've been doing some research on keepers and I've come up with these recommendations (happy to hear others' input though):

- 2 keepers max
- Price for each keeper is the round they were drafted + 2 rounds the following year
- This means 1st & 2nd round players in the draft are automatically ineligible
- 16 rounds of the draft total (meaning 9 starters, 7 bench--would have to adjust our current league settings)
- FA adds are not eligible to be keepers (FAs still very much reward your team that year if they're a breakout player but not allowing them as keepers rewards good drafting & research above adding a guy after a good week)

5.	*puts on fancy voice* As a frequent listener of the SiriusXM Fantasy Channel, I will share that making TDs 4pts is an increasingly common trend among high-level competitive leagues. *end fancy voice* That has no individual bearing on our decision, but just wanted to share that other thoughtful leagues are making this switch and it’s actually where I got the idea from.
6.	If these arguments were unconvincing to you, and you still believe TDs should earn 6 points because they are the most valuable play a player can make, I offer a final challenge: justify why TDs should be exactly 6 points. If they are such a valuable play, why don’t we make them 10 points? Or 20 points?
7.	As an aside, I loved putting this argument together and rest assured I will put forth a similar effort for our weekly power rankings.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: 4.	Arguably the most difficult position to manage in fantasy football is TE. After the top three or so players, there’s a massive drop-off in quality and expected production. Over the past several years, this has meant that many TEs people start are largely TD dependent – that is, their relative value to the opponent’s TE largely rests on if they score a TD or not. For example, the 8 points for one 15 yard catch and a TD points for a TD would heavily outweigh an average TE stat line like 5 points for 3 catches and 35 yards (a 60%  increase in this example). Reducing the point payoff for TDs will make TEs less reliant on touchdowns and will make mid- and lower-tier role player TEs better relative to the field (and in a 12 player league, several of us will undoubtedly be starting mid- and lower-tier TEs). And again – if a TE does score a touchdown, it’s still a valuable play, just not as heavily weighted as it would be if it was worth 6 points.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: Second, I challenge whether those players that exist should be highly valued in fantasy anyway. If your plan would be to start a RB that might only get 3-4 touches a game and just hope to spike a TD, I would liken that to raising preflop with 3/4 offsuit and hoping to spike three of a kind. It will work some of the time, but it’s highly unreliable and impossible to plan for, and even if it works it could result in a lot of feelsbad for your opponent. (Take it from the guy who missed the playoffs in a $200 buy in league because of a Rex Burkhead 2 TD game.)

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: 3.	An argument has been made that this will impact the value of goal-line backs and red zone receiving threats. My response to this is twofold: first, I challenge you to name more than a couple players that truly fill just those roles. For example, Kamara is a big-time goal-line back, but he’s also a three-down back that has a ton of value anyway. Same with red-zone receivers like Devante Adams. I am struggling to think of players that are used almost exclusively to score TDs.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: and third, WRs may be slightly better flex plays than RBs (since their average score compared to average RB scores will be slightly higher because of half PPR points – this also does not strike me as an issue since good flex play RBs will be relatively rare compared to good flex WRs anyway in a competitive half PPR 12-team keeper league). Even with these concessions, values should be relatively unchanged – great players at any position will still be great, and bad players at any position will still be bad.

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: 2.	I think there is a misconception that this would dramatically impact the value of many players. The value of all players in fantasy are relative, not absolute, because you and your opponents must always start the same number of players in the same positions (save for the single flex spot). Since the points for a TD are reduced for all players, it will not significantly affect their relative value. I openly concede it will have three small effects: first, TE relative value will change (in a very positive way I believe, as I will discuss shortly); second, as currently scored, QBs will raise in value (because their portion of a team’s total score will slightly higher than normal if passing TDs remain at 4 – this does not strike me as an issue because each team only starts one QB and there are plenty of startable QBs in fantasy, but it could be addressed by making passing TDs 3 points, for example);

messages.name: Ben Reichard
messages.text: 1.	A primary challenge of fantasy football is managing variance. It’s why we don’t play with defensive players, for example, and why we agreed to other rules like 0.1 points per yard for FG and an additional W/L against league median each week. If one views fantasy as gambling, then managing variance becomes less important and it’s fine having more dice rolls. If one views fantasy as more of a game, one that rewards strategy, planning, and execution, lowering variance is a useful endeavor (to a point, of course, but the very nature of professional sports means that fantasy is always going to have a high amount of variance overall). Reducing the point payoff for a somewhat random single play helps achieve this goal, while still awarding great individual effort and still making it the most valuable play for your fantasy team. 4 points is still a lot of points – this is just a 33% reduction and stacking up several touchdowns would still be a huge asset.

I like TDs worth 4 for QBs and worth 6 for everyone else for two main reasons:

1) If TDs are worth the same for everyone, QBs become OP (making TDs 6 for everyone else keeps other positions very relevant)

2) Keeping TDs at 6 helps to award players who are absolute monsters on the ground but don't get much receiving work (Derrick Henry & Nick Chubb for example). With lowered TD scores those two become average while being undoubtedly top 5 pure runners in the NFL

messages.text:
My votes:
1. Keeper
2. ESPN
3. Sixteen
4a. A system whereby you can get 2 wins/losses per week: 1 win from head to head matchup, the other from whether or not you were in the top half that week
4b. Weeks 1 through 17, except weeks 15, 16, and 17 are a single elimination three-round playoff. Top half of the league makes the playoffs.
4c. Auction
5. $25 buy-in, 3rd place gets money back, 2nd gets 1/3 of remaining, 1st gets the rest
6. In the Summer I'm strawberry blond, in the Winter I'm dirty blond
7. Waffle House
